---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

const data = {
  metaTitle: "Warehouse Management System | All Webbed Labs",
  metaDescription: "How we helped a Melbourne 3PL provider replace a 17-year-old unsupported WMS, cut pick error rates from 2.3% to 0.3%, and reduce monthly stock reconciliation from a full day to 2 hours.",

  industry: "Logistics & Transport",
  tags: ["Warehouse Management", "Barcode Scanning", "3PL", "Shopify Integration", "Order Fulfilment"],

  title: "Warehouse Management System",
  summary: "A Melbourne third-party logistics provider running 1,200 orders per day for 12 client brands was operating on a warehouse management system that had last been updated in 2008. Pick errors were costing thousands per month, stock reconciliation consumed an entire day each month, and new clients took three weeks to onboard. We built a modern WMS that changed all three.",

  heroImageDescription: "Warehouse picker scanning a barcode on a pallet with a Zebra handheld device, alongside the web-based WMS dashboard showing live order queue, pick-to-light assignments, and stock levels by bin location",

  // CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved
  clientOverview: "Southpeak Logistics is a third-party logistics provider based in Melbourne's outer east, operating an 8,500-square-metre warehouse facility that stores and fulfils inventory for 12 client brands across homewares, apparel, and consumer electronics. The company processes approximately 1,200 outbound orders per day and manages inbound receiving for multiple supplier shipments weekly, with 35 permanent warehouse staff working across two shifts.",
  clientSize: "35 staff, 8,500sqm warehouse, 1,200 orders/day",
  clientLocation: "Melbourne, VIC",

  pullQuote: "We knew the old system was holding us back, but we didn't appreciate how much until we saw the new one working. The pick error rate dropping that fast — in the first month — that got everyone's attention, including the clients who'd been quietly frustrated with us.",
  pullQuoteAuthor: "Brendan Lau",
  pullQuoteRole: "General Manager, Southpeak Logistics",

  challenge: [
    "The Southpeak WMS had been purchased in 2007 and installed in 2008. At the time, it was a reasonable choice for a smaller operation — it handled stock receipts, order picking, and basic inventory tracking, and the vendor provided responsive support. By 2023, the vendor had ceased support for the version Southpeak was running, the software ran only on Windows 7 machines that had been kept offline specifically to avoid forced updates, and the handheld scanning devices it supported had been discontinued by the manufacturer. Southpeak was running critical infrastructure on equipment that could not be replaced like-for-like if it failed.",
    "Pick errors were a daily problem with measurable financial consequences. The pick error rate — confirmed by comparing expected outbound item counts to customer return and dispute claims — ran at approximately 2.3% of order lines. Across 1,200 orders per day with an average of 2.8 lines per order, that translated to roughly 78 error lines per day. Not every error resulted in a return — some were short shipments that were re-sent, some were wrong-item substitutions that clients absorbed — but the freight, re-pick, and credit costs were running to approximately $8,000 per month based on Southpeak's own tracking. Client contracts included error-rate SLAs, and two clients were in breach-of-contract territory.",
    "Stock reconciliation was a monthly ceremony that everyone dreaded. On the first Monday of each month, one full shift — all 35 warehouse staff — conducted a manual stocktake. Orders were paused from 6am to 2pm while pickers physically counted stock in each bin location and reconciled it against the WMS records. Discrepancies were investigated and adjusted; sometimes an adjustment reflected a real stock loss, sometimes it reflected a data entry error in the WMS from weeks earlier. The monthly pause cost approximately $14,000 in lost processing capacity and staff overtime.",
    "New client onboarding was the business development bottleneck. Bringing a new client brand onto the Southpeak WMS required manual data entry of every SKU — product codes, descriptions, dimensions, weights, supplier codes, and bin location assignments. For a client with 200 SKUs, this took a data entry administrator approximately three weeks, assuming the client provided clean data. If the client's product data arrived in an inconsistent format (which was the norm), the timeline extended further. Several prospective clients had chosen competing 3PLs during the onboarding delay.",
    "The handheld device situation was becoming untenable. Southpeak had 18 barcode scanning handhelds — an older Zebra model from the same era as the WMS. Twelve were in serviceable condition; six had cracked screens, sticky buttons, or battery issues that made them unreliable. Replacements for this model were no longer manufactured, and the only supply came from secondhand sources on eBay. When a device failed mid-shift, the picker either borrowed from a colleague or reverted to a paper pick list — which defeated the purpose of a WMS and dramatically increased error rates."
  ],

  whyUs: [
    "The general manager had been evaluating WMS options for eighteen months before engaging us. Two enterprise WMS vendors had quoted the project at prices that would have been difficult to justify against Southpeak's revenue. A third, more affordable platform had good features for single-client warehouse operations but its multi-client architecture — needed to keep Southpeak's twelve client brands' inventory properly partitioned — required an enterprise licence tier that brought the cost back to an uncomfortable level.",
    "Our introduction came through a technology broker who was helping Southpeak evaluate options. The general manager's key concerns were continuity of operations during the transition — he was not willing to accept a multi-day system cutover that would pause order processing — and the ability to integrate with the Shopify and WooCommerce stores of his ecommerce-native client brands. Both requirements were familiar to us. We proposed a parallel-run migration strategy and demonstrated a working Shopify webhook integration in our initial presentation. That combination of operational pragmatism and specific technical capability won the work."
  ],

  approach: [
    "We spent three days on-site at the warehouse before writing a line of code. The purpose was not just to understand the existing system but to understand how experienced warehouse staff actually worked within it — which shortcuts they'd developed, which parts of the process they found genuinely difficult, and what their mental model of 'the right way' to do a pick run looked like. Experienced pickers had strong opinions about pick sequencing (aisle order matters enormously for efficiency), how receiving should work when a supplier delivery doesn't match the advance shipping notice, and what information they needed on the handheld screen at the point of scanning.",
    "The Zebra device integration required early investigation. Modern Zebra TC-series handhelds run Android and have a well-documented Android SDK, but the specific communication protocol between the scanner hardware and a web-based WMS had several options. We tested a browser-based approach (rendering the WMS interface in a locked-down Chrome instance on the Zebra device) against a lightweight native Android wrapper around our web application. The native wrapper won on performance and scanner button binding — we could map the Zebra's physical scan trigger to our capture function reliably, which was not consistently achievable in pure browser mode.",
    "Multi-client data partitioning was the most important architectural decision. Each of Southpeak's client brands needed complete isolation of their inventory data — Southpeak's contracts included data confidentiality provisions, and a bug that accidentally showed Client A's stock levels to Client B's account manager would be a serious commercial problem. We implemented client partitioning at the database schema level using PostgreSQL row-level security policies, which meant the application layer couldn't accidentally query across client boundaries regardless of application-level bugs.",
    "The Shopify and WooCommerce integrations were built as a webhook-based event system rather than a polling architecture. When an order is placed in a client's Shopify store, Shopify fires a webhook to Southpeak's WMS within seconds of the transaction. The WMS validates the order, checks stock availability, creates a pick task, and assigns it to the next available picker's queue — all before the customer's confirmation email has finished sending. For the ecommerce clients, this meant Southpeak could offer same-day dispatch on orders placed before 1pm, which was a meaningful competitive advantage for those brands."
  ],

  solution: [
    "The WMS is built around four core workflows: inbound receiving, putaway, pick-and-pack, and outbound despatch. Each workflow is designed around the physical reality of a warehouse — the receiving dock worker sees a receiving screen on a wall-mounted tablet with the expected shipment details; the picker sees a sequenced pick list on their Zebra handheld with bin locations in optimal aisle order; the packing station has a desktop interface for weight capture and label printing; despatch sees a manifesting interface tied to the carrier integrations.",
    "Pick accuracy is enforced through scan-to-confirm at every step. When a picker arrives at a bin location, they scan the bin barcode first, then scan each item barcode before placing it in the tote. If the scanned bin doesn't match the pick instruction, the device vibrates and displays an error. If the scanned item barcode doesn't match the expected SKU or quantity, the same. A picker cannot progress to the next pick line until the current one is confirmed correct. This removes the possibility of a wrong-location or wrong-item pick without making the picker re-key anything — the scan is the confirmation.",
    "Stock levels are maintained in real time by the transaction model: every movement — receipt, putaway, pick, despatch, return, adjustment — creates an immutable transaction record. The current stock level for any SKU in any bin location is calculated from the transaction history, not from a mutable stock field. This means there is no 'drift' between what the system thinks is in a location and what physically moved through it; any discrepancy is a genuine exception, not accumulated data entry noise. Monthly stocktakes still happen, but as a sampling-based verification exercise rather than a full count.",
    "Client brand reporting is a self-service portal that each Southpeak client can access with their own login. The portal shows real-time stock levels, inbound shipment status, order fulfilment rates, and a download of daily despatched orders. For the ecommerce clients, it also shows order status by Shopify order number, allowing their own customer service teams to check despatch status without calling Southpeak. This reduced inbound enquiry calls to Southpeak's client services team by roughly 40% within the first two months.",
    "New client onboarding was redesigned as a self-service data import flow. Clients upload their product catalogue in a CSV or Excel format, and the system runs a mapping interface that lets them align their column headers to the WMS data fields with a dropdown. The mapped data is validated — duplicate SKU codes, missing mandatory fields, and weight anomalies are all flagged before import — and approved in a single click. A client with 200 SKUs can complete the product data setup in under an hour if their data is reasonably clean. Bin location assignments can be done immediately after import using a visual warehouse map interface."
  ],

  implementation: [
    "The migration from the legacy WMS was the highest-stakes part of the project. We could not afford a cutover window that paused order processing, so we built a migration strategy around running both systems in parallel for two weeks. During the parallel period, orders were processed in the new WMS while a read-only sync kept the legacy system's inventory levels updated as a fallback reference. Pickers used the new Zebra TC-series devices with the new system; the legacy handhelds were kept charged and available in case of issues. By day ten of the parallel run, the operations team was confident enough to decommission the legacy system.",
    "Onboarding the twelve existing client brands to the new WMS required migrating their stock records and product data. We built a data migration tool that extracted current stock positions from the legacy system's database (which used a pre-SQL database format that required a custom read library), mapped them to the new schema, and loaded them with a verification step that compared line-item totals before and after migration. The migration ran overnight, and the opening stock position in the new system on day one matched the legacy system's last export to within 0.1% — a small residual discrepancy traced to in-flight picks during the final legacy sync.",
    "Zebra device deployment was handled as a configuration management exercise. We used Zebra's StageNow tool to pre-configure the Android OS on each of the 22 new devices — locking down the home screen to the WMS app, configuring the WiFi connection and network certificate, and setting the scanner button mapping — before the devices were handed to warehouse staff. Configuring each device took approximately eight minutes from factory settings to operational state. Replacing a failed device in production takes the same eight minutes."
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    "The bin location hierarchy in the legacy system had been informally expanded over the years without a consistent naming convention. Some bin locations used a three-segment code (aisle-bay-level); others used a two-segment code; a few had free-text notes appended. When we migrated the bin location data, we discovered 340 location codes that didn't conform to any consistent pattern. Rather than trying to normalise them programmatically, we ran a workshop with the two most experienced warehouse staff to audit and rename every non-standard location before the go-live. This added four days to the migration timeline but meant the new system started with clean, consistent location data rather than inheriting 17 years of naming entropy.",
    "The real-time stock model surfaced a previously invisible problem: a small number of SKUs had negative stock positions in the legacy system. This was possible in the old system because a mutable stock field could be decremented below zero without triggering an error — in practice, it happened when a return was processed against a SKU that had been fully despatch before the return was entered. The new system's immutable transaction model prevented negative positions, which meant the migration couldn't import those records directly. We resolved each case manually before migration by reconciling the historical transactions, but it revealed that the legacy data had a data quality problem that had been invisible for years.",
    "Ecommerce webhook delivery reliability was better than we expected on Shopify but required careful handling on WooCommerce. Shopify's webhook delivery is reliable and includes retry logic with exponential backoff. WooCommerce's webhook delivery depends heavily on the hosting configuration of the client's WordPress site — a client on a shared hosting plan had webhook delivery failures during periods of high traffic on their hosting server, which caused orders to queue rather than process immediately. We added a polling fallback for WooCommerce clients that queries for recent orders every five minutes as a safety net alongside the webhook, which caught the missed deliveries and meant no order was ever delayed more than five minutes regardless of webhook reliability."
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    "Twelve months post-launch, Southpeak used the platform's client onboarding efficiency to sign three new client brands — something the general manager said would have been operationally impossible under the old system. One of the new clients was a fast-growing Australian health and wellness brand with a complex product range and high-velocity ecommerce operations; their onboarding took four days from signed contract to processing live orders.",
    "The operations team is now exploring automated slotting — using the order frequency data captured in the WMS over twelve months to optimise bin location assignments for high-velocity SKUs, moving them closer to the despatch area to reduce picker travel time. We've provided a data analysis of current pick path distances and a proposed bin reassignment that the operations team estimates would reduce average pick times by a further 8 to 12%. The analysis used the WMS's transaction history directly, which is one of the advantages of a system that was designed to capture complete operational data from day one."
  ],

  resultsNarrative: "The metrics below reflect the first twelve months of operation compared to the twelve months prior, using data from Southpeak's own financial records and the WMS transaction logs. The annual saving from error reduction is calculated from Southpeak's internal tracking of return freight, re-pick labour, and client credits attributable to pick errors.",

  metrics: [
    { value: "0.3%", label: "Pick error rate", context: "Down from 2.3% — scan-to-confirm at every pick step" },
    { value: "2hrs", label: "Monthly stock reconciliation", context: "Down from a full-day all-hands stocktake" },
    { value: "4 days", label: "New client onboarding", context: "Down from 3 weeks — self-service data import flow" },
    { value: "+23%", label: "Orders picked per hour per picker", context: "Improved sequencing and zero paper pick lists" },
    { value: "$94K", label: "Annual saving from error reduction", context: "Return freight, re-pick labour, and client credits eliminated" },
    { value: "99.94%", label: "System uptime in first year", context: "Includes planned maintenance windows" }
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: "React", reason: "Web-based WMS interface for receiving, pick management, and client portal" },
    { name: "Node.js", reason: "Backend API handling order processing, stock transactions, and webhook events" },
    { name: "PostgreSQL", reason: "Immutable transaction ledger with row-level security for multi-client data isolation" },
    { name: "Zebra Android SDK", reason: "Native Android wrapper for TC-series handheld devices with scan button binding" },
    { name: "Shopify Webhooks", reason: "Real-time order injection from client ecommerce stores to WMS pick queue" },
    { name: "WooCommerce API", reason: "Order integration for WordPress-based client stores with polling fallback" },
    { name: "Docker", reason: "Containerised deployment for consistent staging and production environments" },
    { name: "AWS (ECS, RDS, S3)", reason: "Managed container hosting, database, and document/report storage" },
    { name: "Zebra StageNow", reason: "Device configuration management for consistent Zebra handheld deployment" },
    { name: "PDF / Label Generation", reason: "Despatch labels, packing slips, and client reporting in structured PDF format" }
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
